                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d825">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">761.93/166: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Crane</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-11-26T17:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 26, 1920—5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 26—10:19 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>405. Department’s 335, November 16, 6 p.m. In a conversation Yen strongly
                    deprecated note of diplomatic corps on Russian affairs. <pb facs="0877" n="779"
                        xml:id="pg_779"/> Claimed he failed to see what interest non-Russian foreign
                    powers had in the matter as Chinese Government willingly offered to negotiate
                    separately on matters interesting to the several governments. Yen especially
                    referred to Russian courts in Chinese Eastern zone the jurisdiction of which
                    American Government had always opposed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Crane</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
